This paper deals with the computation of Voronoi diagrams, which is a fundamental problem in computational geometry. The use of geodesic distances and the fact that the input is a simple polygon suggest that the paper belongs to the computational geometry (cs.CG) sub-category. The algorithm presented in the paper involves data structures and randomization, which are common topics in the data structures (cs.DS) and discrete mathematics (cs.DM) sub-categories. The problem of computing Voronoi diagrams is also relevant to the graph theory (cs.GR) sub-category. Finally, the mention of an open problem posed by Mitchell suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the systems and control (cs.SY) sub-category, which deals with the analysis and control of complex systems.
